241 Section 3. Sections 32-6-231 and 40-12-300, Code of
242 Alabama 1975, are amended to read as follows:
243 "§32-6-231
244 (a) Any individual who submits to the license issuing
245 official a completed special access parking or disability
246 access parking application form approved by the Commissioner
247 of Revenue which includes the physician's certification that
248 he or she is an individual with a disability shall be issued
249 one removable windshield placard displaying the Dynamic
250 Accessibility Symbol, thereby designating the driver of the
251 vehicle or the passenger as being an individual with a
252 disability.
Page 9

disability.
SB94 Enrolled
253 (1) The removable windshield placard shall be prepared
254 by the commissioner in conformity to Public Law 100-641 and
255 rulemaking resulting therefrom.
256 (2)a. The removable windshield placard issued to the
257 individual with a long-term disability shall expire after a
258 maximum period of five years or any period less than five
259 years to be designated by the commissioner. The placard shall
260 clearly reveal the expiration date and shall be designed in
261 accordance with Public Law 100-641 and rulemaking resulting
262 therefrom to hang from the front windshield rearview mirror
263 when the vehicle is parked in a parking space reserved for
264 individuals with disabilities. If the vehicle lacks a rearview
265 mirror, the placard shall be placed on the dashboard.
266 b. The commissioner may require all individuals with
267 long-term disabilities to be recertified by a licensed
268 physician before special access or disability access parking
269 new removable windshield placards may be reissued.
270 (3) In the event that an individual with a disability
271 does not have the distinctive special access or disability
272 access license plate as provided by Sections 40-12-300 to
273 40-12-302, inclusive under Division 3 of Article 5 of Chapter
274 12 of Title 40, upon request, a second placard may be issued.
275 (b) The commissioner may adopt any rules necessary to
276 administer this division.
277 (c) An individual with a temporary disability, who
278 submits to the license issuing official a completed special
279 access or disability access application form approved by the
280 commissioner which includes the physician's certification that
Page 10

commissioner which includes the physician's certification that
SB94 Enrolled
281 he or she is an individual with a temporary disability, shall
282 be issued one temporary removable windshield placard for a
283 period valid up to six months.
284 (d)(1) A removable windshield placard issued to an
285 individual with a long-term or temporary disability shall
286 expire one week following the death of the disabled
287 individual.
288 (2) The executor of the estate of any disabled
289 individual who has been issued a removable windshield placard
290 shall notify the local licensing official of the disabled
291 individual's death either at the time of probate proceedings
292 or within 90 days of the disabled individual's death,
293 whichever comes first.
294 (e) Any special access or disability access placard
295 that is not in conformity with the federal system rule for
296 parking reserved for individuals with disabilities, Public Law
297 100-641, and subsequent Rule 23 C.F.R. § 1235, shall not be
298 recognized as a valid disabled parking credential."
299 "§40-12-300
300 (a)(1) The distinctive license plates provided for
301 herein shall be prepared by the Commissioner of Revenue and
302 shall be issued through the county license issuing officials
303 of the state in the same manner as are other motor vehicle
304 license plates. An applicant for a distinctive plate shall
305 present to the issuing official documentation that he or she
306 is either of the following:
307 a. A parent, stepparent, or legal guardian of a minor
308 or an adult who is an individual with a disability as defined
Page 11

or an adult who is an individual with a disability as defined
SB94 Enrolled
309 in Section 32-6-230.
310 b. An individual with a disability as defined in
311 Section 32-6-230.
312 (2) Upon presentation of the required documentation,
313 the applicant shall be issued the requested number of special
314 access or disability access distinctive license plates upon
315 the payment of the regular license fee, as provided by law.
316 (b) Any private agency, nursing home, church, or
317 charitable institution that submits to the licensing authority
318 proof satisfactory to the commissioner that it operates a
319 motor vehicle for the primary purpose of transporting one or
320 more individuals with disabilities may apply for the
321 distinctive plates. Applicants shall pay the regular fees for
322 license plates, as provided by law.
323 (c) Any government agency that applies for a license
324 plate for a vehicle that it owns for the primary purpose of
325 transporting individuals with disabilities shall be issued the
326 requested number of license plates according to Section
327 40-12-250, with the plate displaying the Dynamic Accessibility
328 Symbol embossed on the plate.
329 (d) The distinctive license plates shall be used only
330 upon and for personally-owned, private, or government owned
331 and operated passenger vehicles, including, but not limited
332 to, vans, station wagons, buses, motorcycles, and pickup
333 trucks, registered in the name of the individual or public or
334 private agency, nursing home, church, or charitable
335 institution making application therefor, and when issued to
336 the applicant shall be used upon the vehicle for which issued
Page 12

the applicant shall be used upon the vehicle for which issued
SB94 Enrolled
337 in lieu of the standard license plates normally issued for the
338 vehicle. This division shall not be construed to require an
339 individual with a disability to display a distinctive special
340 access or disability access license plate. It is specifically
341 provided that this division shall be construed in pari materia
342 with Section 32-6-231. The commissioner may adopt any rules
343 necessary to carry out this division.
344 (e) The commissioner may require all individuals with
345 long-term disabilities to be recertified by a licensed
346 physician before special access parking or disability access
347 parking license plates may be reissued.
348 (f) Notwithstanding any provision of this section, a
349 motor vehicle may not be parked in an area reserved for
350 individuals with disabilities to park, in a manner that
351 violates Section 32-6-233.1, shall be subject to the penalties
352 provided therein. unless the individual with a disability is
353 in the vehicle."
354 Section 4. (a) On or after January 1, 2027, the
355 Department of Revenue shall develop and implement an
356 electronic scanning system through which a scannable barcode
357 or quick response code shall appear on disability placards
358 and, upon scanning, shall link to the disability placard
359 holder's name and the status of the disability placard.
360 (b) The Commissioner of Revenue shall adopt rules as
361 necessary to implement this section. At a minimum, the rules
362 shall address all of the following:
363 (1) The creation of a scannable barcode or quick
364 response code linked to a disability placard holder's name and
Page 13

response code linked to a disability placard holder's name and
SB94 Enrolled
365 the status of the disability placard as active or expired.
366 (2) The appearance of the scannable barcode or quick
367 response code on disability placards.
368 (3) That the system and the information contained
369 within the system may only be accessed by the Department of
370 Revenue and law enforcement agencies enforcing Sections
371 32-6-233 and 32-6-233.1, Code of Alabama 1975.
372 Section 5. This act shall become effective on October
373 1, 2026, except Section 2 shall become effective October 1,
374 2028.
